  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Greening Humanitarian Responses through Recovery, Repair, and Recycling of Solar Products in Camps</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to find a cost-effective solution to repair, reuse and recycle of solar lanterns and solar home systems and their accessories that have been distributed in internally displaced persons and refugee camps in East Africa. The project intends to define a cost-effective approach and put in place activities that would reduce waste, prolong energy access, create jobs, support livelihoods and provide business opportunities. This bold and innovative project is the first to ever look exclusively at the issue of solar waste in displacement settings. In light of this, the pilot will produce and share learnings around the unique factors affecting electronic repair and e-waste management in displacement settings in order to help &#x2018;green&#x2019; existing humanitarian operations in other places. The findings will also act as a proof of concept for a longer-term, potentially commercial operation. Finally, there is scope in the longer term to extend the scale of the project beyond solar products and their accessories (TVs, radios, torches, and fans) to include other forms of e-waste (mobile phones or battery-powered torches).</narrative>
  </description>
